<!DOCTYPE html>
Defines document type and html version.
Browser understand that it is a html file that will be going to load.


Non Semantic Elements (Tells nothing about its content.)
e.g :- <div> , <span>


Semantic Elements
Semantic elements = elements with a meaning.
describes its meaning to both the browser and the developer.
e.g :- <form> , <table> , <article>


<section>	
Defines a section in a document.
A section is a thematic grouping of content, typically with a heading.( sections for introduction, content, and contact information.)
<section>
    <h1>WWF</h1>
    <p>The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) is an international organization working on issues regarding the conservation, research and restoration of the environment, formerly named the World Wildlife Fund. WWF was founded in 1961.</p>
</section>


<article>	
Defines independent, self-contained content.(Forum post, Blog post, Newspaper article)
<article class="browser">
    <h2>Google Chrome</h2>
    <p>Google Chrome is a web browser developed by Google, released in 2008. Chrome is the world's most popular web browser today!</p>
</article>

There is no definitions for nesting article and section so section can contain article or article can contain section.


<header>	
Specifies a header for a document or section
(can contain one or more heading elements (<h1> - <h6>), logo or icon, authorship information, navigational links).


<footer>	
Defines a footer for a document or section
(can contain authorship information, copyright information, contact information, sitemap, back to top links, related documents)


<aside> :- Defines content aside from the page content (like sidebar)
<details> :- Defines additional details that the user can view or hide
<figure> :- Specifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc.
<figcaption> :- Defines a caption for a <figure> element
<main> :- Specifies the main content of a document
<mark> :- Defines marked/highlighted text
<nav> :- Defines navigation links
<summary> :- Defines a visible heading for a <details> element
<time> :- Defines a date/time



List <li>
allows to group a set of related items in lists.

Unordered list <ul>
list items will be marked with bullets ( small black circles) by default.
<ul>
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Apple</li>
</ul>


Ordered list <ol>
list items will be marked with numbers by default.
<ol>
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Apple</li>
</ol>


Description Lists 
<dl> :- A description list is a list of terms, with a description of each term.
<dt> :- description term/name.
<dd> :- description details.

<dl>
  <dt>Coffee</dt>
  <dd>- black hot drink</dd>
  <dt>Milk</dt>
  <dd>- white cold drink</dd>
</dl>

o/p

    Coffee
        - black hot drink
    Milk
        - white cold drink


<table>
tables allows to arrange data into rows and columns.
<table> tag defines an HTML table.
we insert data row wise and not columnwise.
<tr> :- table row.
<th> :- table head.
<td> :- table data/cell.
By default, the text in <th> elements are bold and centered.
By default, the text in <td> elements are regular and left-aligned.

<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Firstname</th>
    <th>Lastname</th>
    <th>Age</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Sam</td>
    <td>Son</td>
    <td>50</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Jack</td>
    <td>Son</td>
    <td>44</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<caption> element to define a table caption. (immediately after the <table> tag.)
colspan attribute to make a cell span many columns. (inside th or td)
rowspan attribute to make a cell span many rows. (inside th or td)



<br> tag
empty tag that inserts a single line break.

<hr> tag
horizontal rule that is used to separate content.



Four core attributes that can be used on most HTML elements(although not all)
id :- used to uniquely identify an element. when to elements have same name it will help to distinguish between both of them.
title :- gives suggested title for the element.
class :- used to associate elements with stylesheets.
style :- defines styles to specific element.



<img> tag  is used to embed an image.
no closing tag (self closing tag).
has two required attributes:-
    src :- specifies path to the image (source).
    alt :- specifies an alternate text for the image (alternate text). if image source is not loaded alternate text will be displayed

